The presence of both significant symptoms including severe diarrhea and weight loss along with confirmed histological findings supports an underlying mechanism involving unregulated gastrin production despite atrophy—most consistent with ectopic gastrin secretion rather than simple auto-immune processes.

\boxed{D}

The correct answer is D – ectopic gastrin secretion – as it best explains the combination of persistent upper GI symptoms, profound diarrhea secondary to excessive acid-induced enzymatic dysfunction, progressive weight loss, and paradoxical hyper-acid state despite parietal cell atrophy seen in endoscopy biopsy results. This contrasts sharply with other options such as serotonin-related tumors or somatostatin excess, neither of which account for these specific pathophysiologic features observed clinically and biologically.

